1
00:00:03,719 --> 00:00:06,517
So, Bernadette, how goes the hunt
for bridesmaid dresses?

2
00:00:06,679 --> 00:00:09,716
Well, if you don't mind looking
like an orange traffic cone, great.

3
00:00:10,680 --> 00:00:13,558
Girlfriends, l have the answer
to our dress problems.

4
00:00:13,720 --> 00:00:15,438
BERNADETTE: Really?
AMY: Twelve years ago...

5
00:00:15,599 --> 00:00:17,555
...my cousin Irene
and her entire family died...

6
00:00:17,720 --> 00:00:21,235
...in a horrific carbon-monoxide accident
the night before her wedding.

7
00:00:22,679 --> 00:00:25,477
-That's horrible.
-Yes and no.

8
00:00:26,199 --> 00:00:28,429
All those bridesmaids dresses
remain unused...

9
00:00:28,599 --> 00:00:30,669
...and available to us for free.

10
00:00:31,999 --> 00:00:34,229
So it seems that cloud
of odorless, deadly gas...

11
00:00:34,400 --> 00:00:36,038
...had a silver lining after all.

12
00:00:36,799 --> 00:00:40,189
Check it out, still in the bags.
The gowns, not the bridesmaids.

13
00:00:43,080 --> 00:00:45,548
I don't know. Dead people's dresses?

14
00:00:45,720 --> 00:00:48,951
Yeah, and cap sleeves? Ehh....

15
00:00:50,080 --> 00:00:51,638
Hmm. I was hoping
you wouldn't notice.

16
00:00:51,799 --> 00:00:54,677
Irene was a slave to a good bargain
when it came to clothes...

17
00:00:54,840 --> 00:00:58,116
...and, sadly, as it turned out,
space heaters.

18
00:00:58,319 --> 00:00:59,718
Ladies, please.

19
00:00:59,879 --> 00:01:04,111
These four walls
once housed an intellectual salon...

20
00:01:04,280 --> 00:01:07,352
...where the mind received
nourishment as well as the stomach.

21
00:01:07,520 --> 00:01:10,353
But through no one's fault, Penny...

22
00:01:11,800 --> 00:01:15,349
...the quality of dinner conversation
in this apartment has declined.

23
00:01:15,520 --> 00:01:18,990
And again, I'm looking at no one
in particular, Penny.

24
00:01:20,520 --> 00:01:23,080
Fine. What would you like
to talk about, Sheldon?

25
00:01:23,280 --> 00:01:25,316
Ugh. "What would you like to talk about,
Sheldon?"

26
00:01:25,479 --> 00:01:27,231
Why do you hate us?

27
00:01:27,960 --> 00:01:30,394
I've prepared a number of topics
that should appeal...

28
00:01:30,559 --> 00:01:33,949
...to both the advanced
and novice conversationalists.

29
00:01:34,119 --> 00:01:35,757
Okay, that time, you looked at me.

30
00:01:36,920 --> 00:01:41,232
Who didn't? Your skin is like alabaster.
Do you even have pores?

31
00:01:43,039 --> 00:01:46,190
Topic one:
"Faster-than-light particles at CERN:

32
00:01:46,360 --> 00:01:47,952
Paradigm-shifting discovery...

33
00:01:48,119 --> 00:01:51,714
...or another Swiss export
as full of holes as their cheese?"

34
00:01:51,879 --> 00:01:53,710
And converse.

35
00:01:55,560 --> 00:01:57,994
-Who wants to look at bridal magazines?
-Oh, me.

36
00:01:58,160 --> 00:02:00,469
Through no one's fault, Sheldon,
we're leaving.

37
00:02:02,360 --> 00:02:05,238
-Wait for moi.
-What? You're leaving?

38
00:02:05,399 --> 00:02:08,675
Sheldon, sometimes you forget,
I'm a lady.

39
00:02:08,880 --> 00:02:10,916
And with that
comes an estrogen-fueled need...

40
00:02:11,079 --> 00:02:14,674
...to page through glossy magazines
that make me hate my body.

41
00:02:18,079 --> 00:02:19,512
-Well.
-New topic:

42
00:02:19,680 --> 00:02:23,798
"Women: Delightfully mysterious
or bat-crap crazy?"

43
00:02:24,439 --> 00:02:26,350
Totally.
What's wrong with cap sleeves?

44
00:02:26,519 --> 00:02:29,033
If you have the right figure for it,
they're adorable.

45
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:58,355
Hey, Amy, what brings you
to our neck of the woods?

46
00:02:58,519 --> 00:03:01,238
Your Neurology Department
loaned me a culture of prions...

47
00:03:01,400 --> 00:03:04,597
...for my research
on bovine spongiform encephalopathy.

48
00:03:07,480 --> 00:03:10,358
She popped by
to borrow a cup of mad cow disease.

49
00:03:10,519 --> 00:03:12,111
[CHUCKLES]

50
00:03:13,239 --> 00:03:17,027
It's hard to make degenerative brain
maladies hilarious, yet somehow you do.

51
00:03:19,040 --> 00:03:21,076
That's fun to have in a lunchroom.

52
00:03:21,239 --> 00:03:23,958
The real fun starts
when you pick the rat to feed it to...

53
00:03:24,120 --> 00:03:27,795
...and maybe you choose the beady-eyed
mother who's been biting you all week.

54
00:03:29,559 --> 00:03:32,995
Please, we're eating. Can we get that
off the table and change the subject?

55
00:03:33,159 --> 00:03:35,673
Can we? Stand back...

56
00:03:35,840 --> 00:03:40,118
...while I turn this conversation
into a "conver-sensation."

57
00:03:40,760 --> 00:03:42,034
This time, it's your fault.

58
00:03:42,760 --> 00:03:44,910
l have 100 alphabetized topics...

59
00:03:45,079 --> 00:03:48,469
...from "Artichoke: Come on, people,
it's just a giant thistle"...

60
00:03:48,640 --> 00:03:53,714
...to "Zzz:
The onomatopoetry of sleep."

61
00:03:54,480 --> 00:03:58,393
Amy, how long would it take
for that mad cow disease to kill me?

62
00:03:59,200 --> 00:04:01,555
I don't know, four or five years.

63
00:04:01,720 --> 00:04:03,790
No, that's not gonna do it.

64
00:04:07,239 --> 00:04:12,233
Oi. Bernadette keeps texting me pictures
of Penny in bridesmaid dresses.

65
00:04:12,840 --> 00:04:14,831
-They're out shopping right now?
-Yeah.

66
00:04:14,999 --> 00:04:17,229
-Just the two of them?
-I guess.

67
00:04:18,519 --> 00:04:20,953
That's cool, that's cool.

68
00:04:21,840 --> 00:04:23,398
Why are they asking me about this?

69
00:04:23,560 --> 00:04:26,552
What guy knows
what a sweetheart neckline is?

70
00:04:33,720 --> 00:04:35,711
[PANTING]

71
00:04:37,239 --> 00:04:40,151
Leonard's coming down
the home stretch.

72
00:04:42,879 --> 00:04:45,598
Come on, horsey, you can do this.

73
00:04:47,320 --> 00:04:50,630
Damn. Come on, thigh muscles,
you can do this.

74
00:04:51,800 --> 00:04:53,995
Yes! First place.

75
00:04:54,520 --> 00:04:55,509
[GASPS]

76
00:04:55,680 --> 00:04:58,672
I would have been a greatjockey
if I weren't too tall.

77
00:04:59,320 --> 00:05:01,709
And scared of horses.

78
00:05:01,879 --> 00:05:02,868
Sheldon, you're up.

79
00:05:03,719 --> 00:05:05,152
-What?
-Come on, it's your turn.

80
00:05:05,320 --> 00:05:07,311
We said we'd get more fresh air.

81
00:05:08,799 --> 00:05:12,508
Sorry. I'm a little distracted.
I can't seem to get in touch with Amy.

82
00:05:12,720 --> 00:05:15,359
I tried e-mail, video chat,
tweeting her...

83
00:05:15,519 --> 00:05:18,397
...posting on her Facebook Wall,
texting her, nothing.

84
00:05:18,559 --> 00:05:21,073
Did you try calling her
on the telephone?

85
00:05:21,560 --> 00:05:22,879
The telephone.

86
00:05:26,079 --> 00:05:28,832
You know, Leonard,
in your own simple way...

87
00:05:29,039 --> 00:05:31,314
...you may be the wisest of us all.

88
00:05:32,200 --> 00:05:33,553
Voicemail.

89
00:05:33,759 --> 00:05:37,274
Tsk. Curiouser and curiouser.

90
00:05:37,440 --> 00:05:40,000
If you're worried,
we can go and see if she's all right.

91
00:05:40,160 --> 00:05:42,594
Okay.
You know, I heard in the news...

92
00:05:42,759 --> 00:05:46,354
...a bobcat has been spotted
in her neighborhood.

93
00:05:46,879 --> 00:05:49,154
I don't think Amy was eaten
by a bobcat.

94
00:05:49,319 --> 00:05:51,674
Who thinks Amy was eaten
by a bobcat?

95
00:05:53,560 --> 00:05:55,312
-You do?
-Leonard...

96
00:05:55,479 --> 00:05:58,039
...l was just mentioning
an interesting local news item.

97
00:05:58,199 --> 00:06:01,874
Now, thanks to you, I'm worried
Amy's been eaten by a bobcat.

98
00:06:02,039 --> 00:06:03,154
Forget about the bobcat.

99
00:06:03,319 --> 00:06:05,594
SHELDON: How can I?
You won't stop talking about it.

100
00:06:07,079 --> 00:06:08,478
[STRUMMING]

101
00:06:08,639 --> 00:06:13,269
[SINGING]
Everybody hurts

102
00:06:13,439 --> 00:06:15,316
Sometimes

103
00:06:15,480 --> 00:06:18,870
Everybody cries

104
00:06:19,040 --> 00:06:20,075
[WHIMPERING]

105
00:06:22,359 --> 00:06:25,908
Everybody hurts

106
00:06:27,280 --> 00:06:29,077
Sometimes.

107
00:06:29,800 --> 00:06:31,950
She sounds weepy.
I don't like weepy. Let's go.

108
00:06:32,119 --> 00:06:35,748
Hey. She's your friend. Step up.

109
00:06:37,200 --> 00:06:40,829
Amy, Amy, Amy. Bye.

110
00:06:41,040 --> 00:06:44,749
-Where are you going?
-l'm single. I don't need this crap.

111
00:06:46,799 --> 00:06:48,312
Sheldon, what are you doing here?

112
00:06:48,480 --> 00:06:51,313
You didn't respond
to any of my electronic communications.

113
00:06:51,799 --> 00:06:52,834
I wanted to be alone.

114
00:06:55,679 --> 00:06:57,556
Would you like to talk about it?

115
00:06:57,719 --> 00:07:02,349
And keep in mind that "no"
is a perfectly viable answer.

116
00:07:03,320 --> 00:07:05,550
Sheldon,
my world is crumbling around me.

117
00:07:05,720 --> 00:07:07,517
Point of order.

118
00:07:07,679 --> 00:07:09,271
As you're in distress...

119
00:07:09,440 --> 00:07:12,512
...it would be customary
for me to offer you a hot beverage.

120
00:07:13,080 --> 00:07:15,469
But I'm a guest in your home...

121
00:07:15,639 --> 00:07:18,836
...so it would be customary
for you to offer me a beverage.

122
00:07:20,880 --> 00:07:23,713
How do you wanna proceed
vis-a-vis beverages?

123
00:07:23,879 --> 00:07:26,916
It doesn't matter. Nothing matters.

124
00:07:28,280 --> 00:07:32,319
If you'd like to take your mind off
what's troubling you...

125
00:07:32,480 --> 00:07:36,234
...uh, word on the street is
a bobcat has been spotted.

126
00:07:37,400 --> 00:07:40,790
Penny and Bernadette went shopping
for bridesmaids dresses without me.

127
00:07:41,760 --> 00:07:46,197
And that made you feel sad?

128
00:07:47,159 --> 00:07:49,275
-Yes.
-I knew it.

129
00:07:50,520 --> 00:07:53,159
Just keep going.
I guess I'm good at this.

130
00:07:54,720 --> 00:07:57,234
It's just, I thought they liked
hanging out with me...

131
00:07:57,400 --> 00:07:59,470
...but I guess I was fooling myself.

132
00:08:00,439 --> 00:08:02,077
When they were over here...

133
00:08:02,239 --> 00:08:05,629
...did you fail to offer them
a beverage?

134
00:08:07,200 --> 00:08:10,510
Because I can see how that could stick
in someone's craw.

135
00:08:12,040 --> 00:08:15,555
Sheldon, I'm gonna ask you something,
and I'd like you to keep an open mind.

136
00:08:15,719 --> 00:08:16,788
Always.

137
00:08:18,119 --> 00:08:20,679
At this moment,
lfind myself craving human intimacy...

138
00:08:20,880 --> 00:08:22,029
...and physical contact.

139
00:08:22,200 --> 00:08:23,633
Oh, boy.

140
00:08:27,160 --> 00:08:30,835
You know ours is a relationship
of the mind.

141
00:08:31,959 --> 00:08:34,837
Proposal:
One wild night of torrid lovemaking...

142
00:08:34,999 --> 00:08:38,150
...that soothes my soul
and inflames my loins.

143
00:08:41,879 --> 00:08:44,313
Counterproposal:

144
00:08:44,480 --> 00:08:47,631
I will gently stroke your head...

145
00:08:47,800 --> 00:08:51,156
...and repeat, "Aw, who's a good Amy?"

146
00:08:54,040 --> 00:08:56,110
How about this?

147
00:08:56,279 --> 00:08:57,428
French-kissing...

148
00:08:57,599 --> 00:09:01,558
...Seven Minutes in Heaven,
culminating in second base.

149
00:09:04,759 --> 00:09:07,478
Neck massage...

150
00:09:08,960 --> 00:09:11,872
...then you get me that beverage.

151
00:09:17,560 --> 00:09:19,471
We cuddle. Final offer.

152
00:09:21,439 --> 00:09:23,077
Very well.

153
00:09:28,920 --> 00:09:30,831
Oh, boy.

154
00:09:51,959 --> 00:09:55,156
I'm just saying,
second base is right there.

155
00:10:01,120 --> 00:10:04,271
Mm. I'm thinking about adopting
some quirky affectation...

156
00:10:04,439 --> 00:10:09,069
...like a pipe or a monocle
or a handlebar mustache.

157
00:10:10,519 --> 00:10:14,353
For all those girls out there
looking for the Indian Monopoly man?

158
00:10:17,919 --> 00:10:21,070
This is not a safe place.
You can't share anything here.

159
00:10:23,560 --> 00:10:26,836
The two of you
need to get your women in line.

160
00:10:28,839 --> 00:10:31,194
-What?
-Last night I was strong-armed...

161
00:10:31,360 --> 00:10:35,148
...into an evening of harp music
and spooning with an emotional Amy.

162
00:10:35,319 --> 00:10:37,628
This on a night
that I had originally designated...

163
00:10:37,800 --> 00:10:40,598
...for solving space-time geometry
in higher-spin gravity...

164
00:10:40,759 --> 00:10:42,556
...and building my Lego Death Star.

165
00:10:44,159 --> 00:10:45,148
And why?

166
00:10:45,360 --> 00:10:47,237
Your gal pals, Penny and Bernadette...

167
00:10:47,399 --> 00:10:50,197
...went out shopping for
some wedding nonsense without Amy...

168
00:10:50,360 --> 00:10:53,557
...an action they took with no thought
as to how it would affect me...

169
00:10:53,720 --> 00:10:56,917
...the future of string theory
or my Lego fun time.

170
00:10:58,560 --> 00:11:00,152
What do you want us to do about it?

171
00:11:00,319 --> 00:11:02,275
You weren't listening
to my topic sentence.

172
00:11:02,439 --> 00:11:03,952
Get your women in line.

173
00:11:05,399 --> 00:11:07,629
Make them apologize to Amy
and set things right.

174
00:11:07,799 --> 00:11:10,438
lam a man of science,
not someone's snuggle bunny.

175
00:11:11,360 --> 00:11:14,272
Why do I have to talk to Penny?
She's not my girlfriend.

176
00:11:14,439 --> 00:11:16,270
You invited her to lunch
four years ago.

177
00:11:16,439 --> 00:11:19,192
Everything about her is on you.
You make it so.

178
00:11:21,839 --> 00:11:23,318
-Moo Shu is Penny.
-Thank you.

179
00:11:23,479 --> 00:11:25,868
-Where's Sheldon?
-Oh, he was up late last night...

180
00:11:26,040 --> 00:11:29,077
...so I gave him an early dinner
and put him to bed.

181
00:11:29,600 --> 00:11:30,589
That's so sweet.

182
00:11:30,759 --> 00:11:33,637
Yeah, but now he's gonna be up
at dawn and wanna play.

183
00:11:35,360 --> 00:11:37,430
So listen, guys,
the reason he was up late...

184
00:11:37,600 --> 00:11:39,636
...is because he was taking care
of Amy.

185
00:11:39,800 --> 00:11:42,394
-She's kind of upset.
-Why?

186
00:11:42,560 --> 00:11:45,791
Her feelings got hurt because
you went dress shopping without her.

187
00:11:45,959 --> 00:11:47,312
I told you that would happen.

188
00:11:47,479 --> 00:11:51,472
This is her first time being a bridesmaid,
and she's getting a little crazy with it.

189
00:11:51,639 --> 00:11:55,473
She keeps on telling us stories about
bridesmaid traditions in other cultures...

190
00:11:55,639 --> 00:11:59,075
...and they're all about getting naked
and washing each other.

191
00:12:06,280 --> 00:12:09,158
She keeps trying to figure out
if our cycles have synced up...

192
00:12:09,360 --> 00:12:12,238
...so we can call ourselves
"The Three Menstra-teers."

193
00:12:14,079 --> 00:12:17,276
We thought it would be easier
to look at dresses one time without her.

194
00:12:17,439 --> 00:12:20,351
-| feel terrible.
-I know, me too. We'll talk to her.

195
00:12:20,520 --> 00:12:22,078
Hey, wait, how did she find out?

196
00:12:23,279 --> 00:12:25,315
Raj did it. Ugh.

197
00:12:27,879 --> 00:12:30,552
And he says he would do it again.

198
00:12:33,600 --> 00:12:34,589
Okay, I'm sorry.

199
00:12:34,799 --> 00:12:36,949
You sent me the picture.
I wasn't thinking.

200
00:12:37,120 --> 00:12:39,873
-Oh, Howie.
-l'm usually pretty good at not blabbing.

201
00:12:40,079 --> 00:12:44,152
You tell me tons of stuff
about these guys, and I never repeat it.

202
00:12:46,720 --> 00:12:49,314
-What do you tell him?
-Oh, you know, just pillow talk.

203
00:12:49,479 --> 00:12:51,834
You guys have nothing to worry about.

204
00:12:51,999 --> 00:12:54,274
Did you talk about us
when we were dating?

205
00:12:54,480 --> 00:12:57,153
No. All your little secrets are fine.

206
00:13:00,920 --> 00:13:03,480
Yes, absolutely fine.

207
00:13:05,439 --> 00:13:07,475
Ha-ha-ha. I'll tell you later.

208
00:13:10,719 --> 00:13:13,472
AMY:
Come on, tumor.

209
00:13:13,680 --> 00:13:14,669
Come on, tumor.

210
00:13:14,840 --> 00:13:18,355
Mama needs
an aggressive little glioblastoma.

211
00:13:19,199 --> 00:13:21,713
Yay, brain tumor.

212
00:13:22,239 --> 00:13:25,470
Probably not the same reaction you had
when you got the news.

213
00:13:26,680 --> 00:13:27,669
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

214
00:13:27,839 --> 00:13:29,397
-Hi.
-Hello.

215
00:13:29,560 --> 00:13:30,993
What are you doing here?

216
00:13:31,160 --> 00:13:32,991
Well, uh, we just wanted to apologize...

217
00:13:33,159 --> 00:13:35,229
...for not bringing you with us
the other day.

218
00:13:35,399 --> 00:13:37,913
That's not necessary.
It's like Sesame Street says:

219
00:13:38,079 --> 00:13:40,115
"One of these things
is not like the others.

220
00:13:40,280 --> 00:13:42,589
One of these things should die alone."

221
00:13:43,720 --> 00:13:45,711
No, come on, Amy,
let us make it up to you.

222
00:13:45,879 --> 00:13:48,313
We'll have a girls' night.
We'll do whatever you want.

223
00:13:48,479 --> 00:13:50,993
We can go down to the Korean baths
and do that thing...

224
00:13:51,160 --> 00:13:53,276
...where we wash each other.

225
00:13:54,560 --> 00:13:57,393
With loofah mitts, no hands.

226
00:13:58,840 --> 00:14:00,637
It's okay. I'm glad this happened.

227
00:14:00,800 --> 00:14:03,030
I can stop pretending
that some beautiful girl...

228
00:14:03,200 --> 00:14:06,476
...and her cute-in-the-right-light friend
wanna hang out with me.

229
00:14:07,080 --> 00:14:10,197
-Amy, we're really sorry.
-Yeah, we feel awful.

230
00:14:10,360 --> 00:14:11,475
Don't. I'll be okay.

231
00:14:11,640 --> 00:14:15,155
You're not the first girls I thought
were friends who ended up shunning me.

232
00:14:15,320 --> 00:14:18,995
It's like elementary school, junior high,
high school, undergrad, grad school...

233
00:14:19,160 --> 00:14:21,720
...and that semester abroad in Norway
all over again.

234
00:14:21,879 --> 00:14:22,994
Oh, come on, Amy.

235
00:14:24,439 --> 00:14:26,236
You don't get it.

236
00:14:26,400 --> 00:14:27,389
Look at this brain.

237
00:14:28,440 --> 00:14:30,192
I don't really want to.

238
00:14:31,079 --> 00:14:32,307
This is us.

239
